<br>
Two sub-catagories:  Eastern and Western.<br>
<br>
My votes:<br>
<br>
Eastern:  Samurai - Part III Duel on Ganryu Island.  Musashi Miyamoto (Toshiro Mifune) and Kojiro Sasaki (Koji Tsuruta) duel on the beach at sunset in the finale of this epic based on the life of Musashi.  Filmed in the days before CGI and color, don't look for acrobatics and flying -- look for people who actually know how to fight...<br>
<br>
Western:  The Sea Hawk.  Captain John Thorpe (Errol Flynn) is a dashing privateer fighting both the Spanish and the intrigue of the English court fostered by Don Alverez (Claude Rains).  Director Michael Curtiz provides both a vivid, moving score and more crashing masts/candelabras/high-back chairs than pitfall provided randomly swinging chains.  Great fun -- and I just like Errol Flynn movies.  Watch for the dueling shadows that are a Curtiz signature!<br>
<br>
What are your votes?<br>
<br>
Raethella <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showUserPublicProfile?gid=perifv>PeriFV</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 50<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(12/8/03 1:02 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm9.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=2188.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Best Ever Swordfight in a Movie!</span><hr size=1> I'm rather partial to the Errol Flynn/Basil Rathbone duel on the beach in Captain Blood. <br>
<br>
I think my very favorite swordfight has to be the one on top of the Cliffs of Despair between Inigo Montoya and Wesley (Princess Bride).<br>
<br>
For group swordfights, I really love the first big swordfight in 1973's Three Musketeers where the musketeers and D'Artagnan fight the Cardinal's men among the drying sheets in the convent courtyard. It was the first time I saw people fighting &quot;dirty&quot; with swords in a movie and I loved it. <br>
<br>
