<br>
I watched a four hour special on the Discovery channel that stated otherwise, Thew.  They were showing how it was amazing for a group in Ohio to perform a 'stone stance,' where they could allow themselves to be punched for 'up to a thousand pounds of pressure' yet show no visible signs of suffering.<br>
<br>
I don't know how hard I punch, but I'm not a professional.  I can and have knocked a three hundred pound free-standing bag over in a single straight.  I don't know much pressure that would take, especially since I'm not 'pushing on it' for a duration.<br>
<br>
I imagine someone who trains at it for hours a day would hit at least twice as hard as I do.  Bruce Lee had a one-inch punch that could knock three men over like dominoes, and could knock a hanging bag off it's chain in a single hit.<br>
<br>
I've been in enough fights to know that a wave block isn't going to work against anyone with decent strength.  I have faith in blocks, just not the way he does them. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showUserPublicProfile?gid=meschaelene>Meschaelene</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 38<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(12/9/03 3:21 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm9.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=2188.topic&index=19>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Drachma...</span><hr size=1> I think the movie you are referring to is &quot;Yojimbo&quot;.  Another Kurosawa film...  Last Man Standing and one of Clint Eastwood westerns (forget which one) were both based on it.<br>
